    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1233271455" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1233271455" />
    <a title="Eric Perry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41243085-eric-perry"><img alt="Eric Perry" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1233271455?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eric Perry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eric Perry" href="/user/show/41243085-eric-perry">Eric Perry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1233271455" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2410123688370918733">Imagine having a writer whom you respect, who also happens to be a Nobel Prize laureate, recommend a few poems. Czeslaw Milosz has done this for us. I like to think of it as a gateway book to poetry in the same way that viewing a performance of one of Shakespeare&apos;s comedies may be a better introduction than reading Julius Caesar in the tenth grade. Milosz has selected poems according to accessibility and length. To those developing a taste for poetry he has selected works that are vivid and enga</span>
  <span id="freeText2410123688370918733" style="display:none">Imagine having a writer whom you respect, who also happens to be a Nobel Prize laureate, recommend a few poems. Czeslaw Milosz has done this for us. I like to think of it as a gateway book to poetry in the same way that viewing a performance of one of Shakespeare's comedies may be a better introduction than reading Julius Caesar in the tenth grade. Milosz has selected poems according to accessibility and length. To those developing a taste for poetry he has selected works that are vivid and engaging in their imagery and language. He has arrange the book by broad topics that are historically and globally favorites of poets--Epiphany, Nature, The Secret of a Thing, Travel, Places, The Moment, People among People, Women's Skin (not erotic poems as much as observations about beauty, aging, self perception), Situations, Nonattachment and History. He introduces throughout the book. There is the general Introduction in which he explains the rational for his his selections, his general philosophy of poetry and its importance for our times. Each section also has introductory comments as well as each individual poem. It reads like a conversation about poetry followed by poems of exquisite worth for their own times and places as well as ours. Milosz suggests rather than lectures, and allows the works to ultimately stand or fall on their own. All are lovingly chosen by a master of the craft wanting to share some of his favorites with those who can appreciate them and draw bystanders into the circle of words and their ability throughout time and place to illuminate. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2410123688370918733" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


