<div id="review_3248627954" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3248627954" />
    <a title="Julia B." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22283757-julia-b"><img alt="Julia B." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1558829445p2/22283757.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3248627954?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julia B." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julia B." href="/user/show/22283757-julia-b">Julia B.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22283757-julia-b?shelf=books-that-changed-my-life">books-that-changed-my-life</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22283757-julia-b?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3248627954" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3757068549545201537"><i>Epiphany may also mean a privileged moment in our life among the things of this world, in which they suddenly reveal something we have not noticed until now, and that something is like an intimation of their mysterious, hidden side. In a way, poetry is an attempt to break through the density of reality into a zone where the simplest things are again as fresh as if they were being seen by a child.</i> (5)<br/><br/>So I am not a big poetry reader. My reading mostly consists of (1) romance novels, (2) academic h</span>
  <span id="freeText3757068549545201537" style="display:none"><i>Epiphany may also mean a privileged moment in our life among the things of this world, in which they suddenly reveal something we have not noticed until now, and that something is like an intimation of their mysterious, hidden side. In a way, poetry is an attempt to break through the density of reality into a zone where the simplest things are again as fresh as if they were being seen by a child.</i> (5)<br /><br />So I am not a big poetry reader. My reading mostly consists of (1) romance novels, (2) academic history papers, and (3) medieval texts written by monks who have been dead for a thousand years ((omg idk I'm just so ~quirky~ like that)). I was excited for this book to arrive at my doorstep because, while I have a few poets I'm devoted to like Anne Carson and Sylvia Plath, I don't have an anthology of multiple different poets, especially not ones from different places and time periods covering a range of themes. Czesław Miłosz was a godsend. I needed him to handpick these simple, short poems and I also needed him to lay out the meaning and context of each poem like I was in first grade and the only poet I knew was Dr. Seuss. (I am a very, very bad poetry-reader, you guys. This point cannot be overemphasized.) The intentions of these poems are distilled; no words are wasted. The simplicity of language in most of them is just so beautiful and comforting and moving. I have accrued so many new favourite poets I didn't even know existed and I am 100% absolutely looking them all up. There are also a number of poems written by poets who are very well-known, like Walt Whitman and the ever-beloved Rumi (and I'm sure the Chinese poets are also very famous, I just hadn't encountered them myself). So, this book was perfect for me. I fell in love with poetry.<br /><br />But speaking of those Chinese poets... I would like to address the concerns other people have raised in their Goodreads reviews; concerns that I think are completely valid, but ultimately subjective. I didn't mind that there were so many poems from Ancient China, because I had never read them before and I loved them. Same goes for all the 20th-century Eastern European authors. This anthology comes across as a deeply personal selection for Miłosz and so it reflects his own tastes more than it does a truly diverse international scope. There are certainly better anthologies for that purpose. What this particular collection aimed to do is capture poems of simple observation, which was/is a very popular genre in Chinese poetry, so it makes sense to me that so many were there. I <i>could</i> be upset that no medieval monks were included—but I am not, because they would make everything about Jesus, and that's not what this collection is about (no shade on them though). So to conclude, for me <i>personally</i> this worked wonders, but I do think it's a question of what you're looking for.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3757068549545201537" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

