    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2957648434" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2957648434" />
    <a title="Victoria Foote-Blackman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37043765-victoria-foote-blackman"><img alt="Victoria Foote-Blackman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1603830764p2/37043765.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2957648434?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Victoria Foote-Blackman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Victoria Foote-Blackman" href="/user/show/37043765-victoria-foote-blackman">Victoria Foote-Blackman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37043765-victoria-foote-blackman?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2957648434" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer351987644168663917">A remarkable compendium of international poetry, with each poem lovingly selected, introduced and commented on by the late great 20th century Polish poet Czeslaw Milosz (1911-2004). It was first published in 1996. He has organized some 300 poems into unusual, overarching themes: Epiphany, Nature, The Secret of a Thing, Travel, Places, The Moment, People Among People, Woman&apos;s Skin, Situations, Nonattachment, and History. Some of these categories are more successful than others, and some could hav</span>
  <span id="freeText351987644168663917" style="display:none">A remarkable compendium of international poetry, with each poem lovingly selected, introduced and commented on by the late great 20th century Polish poet Czeslaw Milosz (1911-2004). It was first published in 1996. He has organized some 300 poems into unusual, overarching themes: Epiphany, Nature, The Secret of a Thing, Travel, Places, The Moment, People Among People, Woman's Skin, Situations, Nonattachment, and History. Some of these categories are more successful than others, and some could have had better headings. (For "Woman's Skin" something simply like "Touch" would not only have been more pc but more accurate as well.)<br /><br />Milosz is not bashful about his choices. He clearly has little time for the 20th century's all too frequent highly personal but obscure verse much touted and little understood, and which has given poetry such a bad name. He deliberately omits T.S. Eliot's The Waste Land, for example. In the general introduction Miloscz writes: "My proposition consists in presenting poems whether contemporary or a thousand years old, that are, with few exceptions, short, clear, readable and, to use a compromised term, realist, that is, loyal toward reality and attempting to describe it as concisely as possible. Thus they undermine the widely held opinion that poetry is a misty domain eluding understanding." The result is a highly readable, yet deeply textured volume that explores all manner of human and animal existence, rich with observation and of feeling, from across the globe. Many works are translated, with the translator receiving full credit.<br /><br />Milosz gives his own countrymen and women their rightful due, including some of the work of such remarkable poets as Anna Swir, and Wislawa Zymborska. In "Nature" Miloscz has also included a number of remarkably prescient and insightful poems about animals and our ambiguous relationship to them. He is also deeply informed and guided by Buddhist teachings and their impact on any number of poets is beautifully served here. Chinese poetry is present throughout these pages and most especially and predictably in the section called "Nonattachment." In the last section, "History," he clearly speaks of himself and his long commitment to political and social ideals when he writes: "Poets have been internally divided, knowing that they should serve art, but at the same time feeling a moral compulsion to be politically committed." Alas, while some of the poems are breathtakingly powerful others are heavy-handed, or lose something in translation. But this is quibbling. Mostly this volume is a a mother lode of remarkable international voices, hailing from many countries and across the centuries.</span>
  <a data-text-id="351987644168663917" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

