<div id="review_3450640138" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3450640138" />
    <a title="R. Allain" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/116729564-r-allain"><img alt="R. Allain" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3450640138?book_show_action=true">Jul 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="R. Allain" class="user" itemprop="url" name="R. Allain" href="/user/show/116729564-r-allain">R. Allain</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3450640138" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13317163622569121430">For me, and one must suspect there are others, poetry labors under an unfortunate cloud. A cloud of inaccessibility. While one grasps by its nature - not to mention its penchant for elitism - poetry operates on elevated terrain. But like Moses, it must (or at least should occasionally) leave the damn summit. And with Czeslaw Milosz&apos; deft powers of finding gems in this genre, his selections and brief comments seldom disappoint. For herein, the Nobel laureate performs a considerable literary, and </span>
  <span id="freeText13317163622569121430" style="display:none">For me, and one must suspect there are others, poetry labors under an unfortunate cloud. A cloud of inaccessibility. While one grasps by its nature - not to mention its penchant for elitism - poetry operates on elevated terrain. But like Moses, it must (or at least should occasionally) leave the damn summit. And with Czeslaw Milosz' deft powers of finding gems in this genre, his selections and brief comments seldom disappoint. For herein, the Nobel laureate performs a considerable literary, and dare I say humanitarian, mission: salvaging powerful and often obscure poems from the dank musty archives. Savor these marvels slowly. In measure. . Carefully. As one might treasure a fleeting visit from a hummingbird or a friend. Aren't the joys immense - and lasting? By the way, a very thoughtful gift, too.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13317163622569121430" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


